<HEADLINE>
<P>
BUSH AND ASSAD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Why does our President meet eagerly with the Syrian head of state, our former 
enemy, Hafez Assad, instead of Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein, our former friend? 
</P>
<P>
Hussein, for all the wrongs he may have done, has shed no Yankee blood, whereas 
Hafez Assad has been accused of master-minding the terrorist attack on the 
Lebanon Marine headquarters that killed 241 American Marines. 
</P>
<P>
Might it not be more to the point and far less costly if Bush and Hussein could 
share a meal together and talk turkey? It wouldn't be as spectacular as Bush's 
well-staged desert extravaganza on Thanksgiving Day, but it might be more 
productive, especially if both leaders would give a little to gain a peaceful 
settlement. 
</P>
<P>
Surely both men are smart enough to know that war gains nothing but loses 
lives, dollars and the very property they are trying to save. 
</P>
<P>
ALBERT JOHNSON 
</P>
<P>
Laguna Hills 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Drawing, Syria's Hafez Assad 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
