<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: ART 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CLAUDIA PUIG, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cafe Break: A Parisian truck driver transporting paintings worth more than $5 
million stopped at a cafe, leaving the ignition keys on the dashboard. 
</P>
<P>
Thieves drove off with the loot Wednesday, police said. Fifty canvases by 
Watteau, Fragonard, Rubens and others from Flemish, Dutch and French schools 
were on board the truck when the driver stopped just before midnight. When he 
emerged, he found that the truck had vanished with its contents. The artworks 
were being transported from Paris, where they had been on display, to 
Strasbourg in eastern France, where they were to have been auctioned today. 
CLAUDIA PUIG 
</P>
</TEXT>
