<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: SIMI VALLEY; 
</P>
<P>
DEADLINE EXTENDED FOR PANEL APPLICANTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CARLOS V. LOZANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The deadline for submitting applications for the Simi Valley Planning 
Commission has been extended from today to Monday, city officials said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
To be eligible for appointment to the five-member panel, applicants must be 
residents of Simi Valley and not be employed by the city. 
</P>
<P>
There are four open seats on the commission, one of which became vacant when 
the chairwoman, Judy Mikels, was elected to the City Council on Nov. 6. 
</P>
<P>
Formal nominations and public interviews of the nominees by the council are 
scheduled for the council's Monday meeting. 
</P>
<P>
Each member of the City Council is responsible for the nomination of one 
planning commissioner. The terms of the commissioners are concurrent with the 
term of the nominating council member. 
</P>
<P>
Mayor Gregory Stratton, who was reelected to a third term this month, Mikels 
and another newly elected council member, Sandi Webb, will each be responsible 
for nominating a planning commissioner. Because Mikels was Councilman Bill 
Davis' appointee to the planning panel, he will also have to select a new 
member to sit on the commission. 
</P>
<P>
The commission, which advises the council on development matters, generally 
meets two Wednesday evenings a month. CARLOS V. LOZANO 
</P>
</TEXT>
