<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE BUTCHER: GOOD WURST IS THE BEST OF MEATS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MERLE ELLIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
If you have read this column with any regularity throughout the years, you are 
aware that I am something of a "nut" for sausage. 
</P>
<P>
To my taste, a good wurst is the best of meats. My wife and I had dinner not 
long ago at Campton Place, the lovely little hotel on Stockton Street in San 
Francisco that the talented young chef Bradley Ogden made famous. Ogden is no 
longer at Campton Place; but fortunately for those of us who live in Marin 
County, he moved to Marin and opened his own place -- the Lark Creek Inn in 
Larkspur. Campton Place was lucky to have Jan Birnbaum, another young and 
talented chef, there to take over when Ogden left. 
</P>
<P>
Not only did he work with Ogden for some time, Birnbaum spent four years with 
Paul Prudhomme in New Orleans before heading off to New York to take over as 
chef at the Quilted Giraffe. He then stopped off for a spell to cook at the 
Rattlesnake Club in Denver before moving on to San Francisco. Campton Place is 
fortunate. 
</P>
<P>
One night after dinner, Birnbaum joined us for coffee. In almost no time, after 
"How's Brad doing?" and "Have you heard from Paul?" the conversation turned to 
sausage -- Birnbaum is a sausage "nut" too. "I've got a couple new ones that I 
think you'll like. I'll fax you the recipes." He did, and I did, and I think 
you will like them also. 
</P>
<P>
CHICKEN-FENNEL SAUSAGE 
</P>
<P>
3 pounds chicken thigh meat 
</P>
<P>
3 pounds pork butt 
</P>
<P>
5 cloves garlic, chopped 
</P>
<P>
1/4 cup fennel seeds 
</P>
<P>
2 tablespoons paprika 
</P>
<P>
2 teaspoons white pepper 
</P>
<P>
1 tablespoon black pepper 
</P>
<P>
2 teaspoons cayenne pepper 
</P>
<P>
1/2 bunch Italian parsley, chopped 
</P>
<P>
1 bunch fresh sage, chopped 
</P>
<P>
1/3 cup Pernod 
</P>
<P>
Hog casings 
</P>
<P>
Cut chicken and pork into strips appropriate for grinding. Combine chicken, 
pork, garlic, fennel seeds, paprika, white pepper, black pepper, cayenne 
pepper, parsley, sage and Pernod in stainless steel or glass bowl. Let stand in 
refrigerator overnight to marinate. 
</P>
<P>
Grind mixture twice through medium plate of meat grinder. Stuff into hog 
casings and twist into links. Makes about 6 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
DUCK AND APPLE SAUSAGE 
</P>
<P>
1 pound pork fatback 
</P>
<P>
1 1/2 pounds duck meat 
</P>
<P>
1 1/2 pounds pork butt 
</P>
<P>
1 quart unfiltered apple juice, reduced to 1/2 cup 
</P>
<P>
1/2 teaspoon ground cumin 
</P>
<P>
1/2 teaspoon cayenne 
</P>
<P>
1/2 teaspoon chili powder 
</P>
<P>
1/2 teaspoon paprika 
</P>
<P>
1 to 1 1/2 teaspoons seasoned salt 
</P>
<P>
3 cups diced pippin apples 
</P>
<P>
1 cup yellow mustard seeds 
</P>
<P>
2 tablespoons finely chopped garlic 
</P>
<P>
1 cup chopped Italian parsley 
</P>
<P>
1 tablespoon chopped fresh sage 
</P>
<P>
1 tablespoon chopped fresh thyme 
</P>
<P>
1 tablespoon chopped fresh rosemary 
</P>
<P>
Hog casings 
</P>
<P>
Cut fatback, duck and pork butt into 1-inch cubes. Simmer apple juice in 
saucepan until reduced to about 1/2 cup, then cool. 
</P>
<P>
Combine meats with apple juice, cumin, cayenne, chili powder, paprika, seasoned 
salt, diced apples, mustard seeds, garlic, parsley, sage, thyme and rosemary in 
stainless steel or glass bowl. Mix well. Let stand in refrigerator overnight to 
marinate. 
</P>
<P>
Grind mixture twice through medium plate of meat grinder. Stuff into hog 
casings and twist into links. Makes about 4 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
CHICKEN-MUSHROOM SAUSAGE 
</P>
<P>
1 1/2 pounds chanterelle mushrooms 
</P>
<P>
1 tablespoon olive oil 
</P>
<P>
1 pound pork fatback 
</P>
<P>
3 pounds pork butt 
</P>
<P>
3 pounds chicken meat 
</P>
<P>
2 bunches thyme, chopped 
</P>
<P>
1 bunch Italian parsley, chopped 
</P>
<P>
1 bunch sage, chopped 
</P>
<P>
1 head garlic, chopped 
</P>
<P>
1/2 cup rich chicken stock 
</P>
<P>
3 tablespoons cayenne pepper 
</P>
<P>
Salt, pepper 
</P>
<P>
1/2 cup fennel seeds 
</P>
<P>
Hog casings 
</P>
<P>
Place mushrooms in roasting pan with olive oil. Roast in 250-degree oven until 
somewhat dry (some moisture needs to evaporate). Dice small enough to fit 
through piping nozzle of sausage stuffer. 
</P>
<P>
Cut fatback, pork butt and chicken meat into 1-inch cubes. Combine meats with 
thyme, parsley, sage, garlic, chicken stock and cayenne. Season to taste with 
salt and pepper. 
</P>
<P>
Grind once through large die and once through medium die. Fold in fennel seeds 
and mushrooms. Stuff into hog casings. Makes about 8 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
Note: To cook, poach sausage lightly and then roast until cooked to medium 
rare. Cool and slice into medallions. 
</P>
<P>
 For more information on sausage and such, plus all the recipes that you may 
have missed if you haven't been reading this column regularly, send a 
self-addressed, stamped envelope to Sausage and Such, P.O. Box 907, Tiburon, 
Calif. 94920. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
