</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A newspaper reported today that police uncovered a plot to kill President Bush 
during his visit here next week, but government officials said the report was 
unfounded. 
</P>
<P>
"There is no confirmation of supposed plans to assassinate President Bush," 
Interior Minister Julio Mera Figueroa said. 
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Embassy refused to comment on the report by the sensationalist daily 
tabloid, Diario Popular. 
</P>
<P>
Police arrested a Bolivian on suspicion of membership in a terrorist group. But 
the judge in charge of the case, Alberto Duran, said, "There is no evidence of 
a plan against the life of Mr. Bush." 
</P>
<P>
The Bolivian was identified as Carlos Anibal Monzon Novena, 41. 
</P>
<P>
Diario Popular claimed that Monzon Novena was the leader of a group called the 
Union of Revolutionary Workers that planned to attack Bush during his 22-hour 
visit in Argentina on Dec. 5-6. 
</P>
<P>
The paper reported that Monzon Novena was imprisoned from 1977 to 1983 during 
the military dictatorship for alleged guerrilla activities and that his group 
is a spinoff from the Revolutionary Army of the People that tried to overthrow 
Argentina's governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
