MCDONNELL DELIVERS 1ST TRI-JET 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
McDonnell Douglas today delivered its first $100-million MD-11 tri-jet, 
culminating a four-year program that the aerospace company hopes will bring $40 
billion in new revenue during the next five years. 
</P>
<P>
"We anticipate recouping our investment three years into the program," said 
Robert Hood, president of the company's Douglas Aircraft subsidiary, which 
built the long-distance, fuel-efficient jetliner at its Long Beach plant. 
</P>
<P>
Hood, speaking at a morning ceremony turning over the jetliner to Finnair, said 
development costs of the plane totaled more than $700 million and that 
estimated total costs so far have reached $2.8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
The company, he said, has 174 firm orders for the MD-11, each with a price tag 
of $100 million. 
</P>
<P>
The MD-11 is an updated version of the wide-bodied DC-10. 
</P>
